James Joseph Marshall (February 3, 1936 – March 24, 2010) was an American photographer and photojournalist who is best known for his iconic images of musicians of the 1960s and 1970s.
Marshall was born in Chicago, Illinois, but his family moved to San Francisco, California, when he was two years old.
After serving several years in the Air Force, he returned and moved to New York.
One famous story concerned a CEO who offered to buy the camera that he used to shoot Jimi Hendrix at Woodstock for $25,000 (in 1973) which he refused.
His photos of 1960s and 1970s musicians, taken both on stage and off without any direction or posing, were possible because of the exceptional access musicians allowed him.
Other photographic assignments included shooting the Indianapolis 500 in 2005 for Autoweek and the 2007 introduction of the Nissan GT-R.
